> [zero](#comment_1_1DLf7WXLCVK3VyLtV3gawnBjTynYeRyhgh): Hi, I tried to configure my zeroblog to accept the alternativ IDs, like KaffieID, and I did on ZeroNet/data/1zite_direction/data/users/content.json

Looks like your content.json is correct. Did you add the right code to allow *selecting* the cert? In your javascript files there should be something like this:

```
Page.cmd("certSelect", {
		"accepted_domains": ["kaffie.bit", "zeroid.bit"],
		"accept_any": true
		});
```

'accept_any' will make anything accepted (but you'd still need them listed in the content.json for some reason). I like to make sure kaffie.bit is listed under 'accepted_domains'. For the record, that's literally copied+pasted from this blog ;).

> [ssdifnskdjfnsdjk](#comment_2_1L4dZcDF2maSKHDy788yhxpYnBWnXadUtS): The step "1. Install CJDNS" is a bit confusing for a Windows user. I am unsure if i need to follow text starting from "Generate a new config". Maybe you should add sub-sections under "1. Install CJDNS". For example:A) WINDOWSB) MAC or LINUXso it is easier to read. Btw as a noob it also confuse me that i do not see Linux mentioned in the tutorial.

The installer will install cjdns for you, but you still need to add the peer. I didn't install on windows so I'm not sure what the exact process is. Does it pop open a text file? If so that's what you need to edit. The instructions on the download page should walk you through it.

Namely on these steps:

>Once you have some peering information (a block of JavaScript code), you can add a peer to your node. Open the Start menu and go to "CJDNS for Windows" and then "Configure cjdns".
Find the line "//Ask somebody who is already connected", and paste your peering credentials directly after that line. If you have multiple peers, be sure to separate them with commas!

That should open up the config file. The last little bit of step one on my guide:

>You'll want to add a peer that's connected to the hyperboria network already, though if you just want private use you can connect to a friend or whoever is on the cjdns network you want to use ZeroNet on. LAN peers are auto-configured.

>One such public peer that you can use is:

Is relevant here. Since this is just instructions on how to set up a peer.

Step 2 (configuring zeronet) is the same on every platform.

> [piloth](#comment_1_1FKuNsExQML7APuNmkCV8uzB5pKupcmnck): Thank you so much for this. It had one unexpected benefit for me. I use my smartphone tethered to my computer exclusively for internet because of where I live. My port for ZeroNet now shows open after installing and running CJDNS. I went to the Mapping Hyperboria site and I had a question. How do I find the peer info? I know this may sound silly, but I am a total noob when it comes to this. Thanks again!

It's not silly at all. So the  site I linked (fc00.org) is a map of the hyperboria/cjdns network. To find more peers you can... ask them directly. As cjdns is meant to be a sort of friend network. Though more realistically since we're all anons you'll want to poke around and find what are called "public peers". You can either find them on clearnet (search around for the info. There's a lot [here](https://github.com/hyperboria/peers) but I haven't checked to see if they're up) or you can take cjdns ips from fc00.org and plug them into your browser (such as: http://[fc6a:30c9:53a1:2c6b:ccbf:1261:2aef:45d3]/ ). Clicking around sites like this is kinda tedious, slow, and may not have a 100% rate (as not all nodes are hosting websites). And even less will have public peering info. 

As for your node... I'm having a hard time connecting to it. Bad peering info? Node not up? You'll want to make sure you can connect to hyperboria/cjdns sites, as that'll ensure you're connected properly to the network (which I can't seem to reach you atm).

